  <static seed="1128" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalExpressionAlgebraSkills/simplifyRationalExpressions10.pg">
    <statement><p>Select all correct simplifications, ignoring possible domain restrictions.</p>
<p><var form="checkboxes">
<li>
<p><m>\frac{10(x-9)}{x -9}=10</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\frac{x+9}{x}=9</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\frac{10 x+9}{x + 9}=10</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\frac{10 x+9}{10}=x+9</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\frac{x+9}{x+10}=\frac{9}{10}</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\frac{x}{10 x}=\frac{1}{10}</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\frac{9 x}{x}=9</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\frac{9}{x+9}=\frac{1}{x+1}</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\frac{x+9}{9}=x</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\frac{x+ 9}{x+9}=1</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\frac{9}{x+9}=\frac{1}{x}</m></p>
</li>
</var></p>
</statement>
    <solution><p>The correct answer is AFGJ.</p>
<p>We may not cross out common terms when the operation is addition or subtraction. For example, the following is <alert> incorrect </alert>:</p>
<p><m>\frac{1+2}{2+2} = \frac{1}{2}</m> (incorrect)</p>
<p>Otherwise, we are saying <m>\frac{3}{4} = \frac{1}{2}</m>.</p>
<p>We may cross out common terms when the operation is multiplication. For example, the following is correct:</p>
<p><m>\frac{2x}{2} = \frac{x}{1} = x</m></p>
<p>We may cross out common factors like <m>x+9</m> when the "major" operation is multiplication. For example, the following is correct:</p>
<p><m>\frac{10(x+9)}{x+9} = \frac{10}{1} = 10</m></p>
</solution>
